If one of our former assumptions is correct, it would seem that before the work had been going on very long it became evident to the master of the scriptoriam that the number of scribes whom he could set at this particular task was going to grow less rather than more, and that he was therefore compelled to give to a smaller number of men a relatively larger amount of work than he had originally planned for each. This would explain why the blocks of text written by the same hand show such adecided tendency to increase in length as the work goes on.
